@startuml

title Shelve Work Order via Application Chat\n(with required code changes)

participant "ApplicationChatHandler" as handler
participant "ToolProvider\n(MCP Loopback Client)" as toolProvider
participant "MCP HTTP Endpoint\n(/mcp)" as mcpEndpoint
participant "ChatClientFactory" as factory
participant "IChatClient\n(Azure OpenAI)" as chatClient
participant "WorkOrderTools\n(MCP Server)" as mcpTools
participant "ReferenceResources\n(MCP Server)" as mcpResources
participant "StateCommandHandler\n(DataAccess)" as stateHandler
database "DataContext\n(EF Core)" as db

autonumber

== Discover MCP Tools ==

handler -> toolProvider : GetToolsAsync()
toolProvider -> mcpEndpoint : HTTP ListTools\n(loopback to /mcp)
mcpEndpoint --> toolProvider : Tool list:\n[list-work-orders, get-work-order,\ncreate-work-order,\nexecute-work-order-command,\nlist-employees, get-employee]
toolProvider --> handler : IList<AITool>

== Build Chat Messages ==

handler -> handler : Create List<ChatMessage>\n- System: "You are a helpful AI\nassistant for work order mgmt..."\n- System: "Limit to 3 sentences"\n- System: "Currently logged in\nuser is {username}"\n- (prior chat history)\n- User: "Shelve work order WO-001"

== Get Chat Client ==

handler -> factory : GetChatClient()
factory --> handler : IChatClient\n(with UseFunctionInvocation)

== LLM Conversation with Tool Calls ==

handler -> chatClient : GetResponseAsync(\nchatMessages, chatOptions)

chatClient -> chatClient : Send to Azure OpenAI API\nwith tool definitions

note right of chatClient
  LLM analyzes the prompt and
  decides it needs to:
  1. Look up the work order
  2. Execute the shelve command
end note

== Tool Call 1: Get Work Order Details ==

chatClient -> mcpEndpoint : invoke tool:\nget-work-order\n{ workOrderNumber: "WO-001" }
mcpEndpoint -> mcpTools : GetWorkOrder(bus, "WO-001")
mcpTools -> db : Send(WorkOrderByNumberQuery\n("WO-001"))
db --> mcpTools : WorkOrder entity
mcpTools --> mcpEndpoint : JSON with work order details\n(Status: "InProgress",\nAssignee: current user)
mcpEndpoint --> chatClient : Tool result

chatClient -> chatClient : LLM sees status=InProgress\nand decides to shelve

== Tool Call 2: Execute Shelve Command ==

chatClient -> mcpEndpoint : invoke tool:\nexecute-work-order-command\n{ workOrderNumber: "WO-001",\n  commandName:\n  "InProgressToAssignedCommand",\n  executingUsername: "{username}" }
mcpEndpoint -> mcpTools : ExecuteWorkOrderCommand(\nbus, "WO-001",\n"InProgressToAssignedCommand",\n"{username}")

note right of mcpTools #FFD2D2
  **CODE CHANGE 1** (WorkOrderTools.cs:122-128)
  Add to the switch statement:
  ""InProgressToAssignedCommand""
    => new InProgressToAssignedCommand(
         workOrder, user)
end note

mcpTools -> mcpTools : Resolve command via switch\nto InProgressToAssignedCommand
mcpTools -> mcpTools : command.IsValid()\n(checks status=InProgress\nand user==Assignee)
mcpTools -> stateHandler : Send(InProgressToAssigned\nCommand)

== State Transition: InProgress -> Assigned ==

stateHandler -> stateHandler : command.Execute()\nSets status to Assigned
stateHandler -> db : Attach & Update WorkOrder
db --> stateHandler : SaveChangesAsync()
stateHandler -> stateHandler : Log: "{user} has shelved\nwork order WO-001"
stateHandler --> mcpTools : StateCommandResult

mcpTools -> mcpTools : FormatWorkOrderDetail(\nresult.WorkOrder)
mcpTools --> mcpEndpoint : JSON: work order\n(Status: "Assigned")
mcpEndpoint --> chatClient : Tool result

== LLM Final Response ==

chatClient -> chatClient : LLM composes natural\nlanguage response
chatClient --> handler : ChatResponse:\n"Work order WO-001 has been\nshelved. It has been moved\nfrom InProgress back to\nAssigned status."

== Required Code Changes ==

note over mcpTools #FFD2D2
  **CHANGE 1: WorkOrderTools.cs - execute-work-order-command switch (line 122)**
  Add case to the commandName switch expression:
  ----
  ""InProgressToAssignedCommand"" => new InProgressToAssignedCommand(workOrder, user),
  ----
  This enables the MCP tool to create the shelve command.
end note

note over mcpTools #FFD2D2
  **CHANGE 2: WorkOrderTools.cs - Tool description (line 86)**
  Update the [Description] attribute to include:
  ----
  "InProgressToAssignedCommand (shelve - moves InProgress back to Assigned)"
  ----
  So the LLM knows the shelve command exists and when to use it.
end note

note over mcpTools #FFD2D2
  **CHANGE 3: WorkOrderTools.cs - Error message (line 133)**
  Update the error message to list InProgressToAssignedCommand
  as an available command.
end note

note over mcpResources #FFD2D2
  **CHANGE 4: ReferenceResources.cs - status-transitions (line 56-59)**
  Add the shelve transition to the InProgress status:
  ----
  InProgress = new[] {
    new { Command = "InProgressToCompleteCommand", TargetStatus = "Complete" },
    new { Command = "InProgressToAssignedCommand", TargetStatus = "Assigned" }
  }
  ----
  So the LLM resource accurately reflects all valid transitions.
end note

@enduml
